[Event "Eric's Classical Tournament Games: Eric (953) vs Bruce Draney (1835) Nebraska HOF 2025 Round 1 0-1"]
[Date "2025.05.31"]
[Result "*"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/ticklefist84"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "A34"]
[Opening "English Opening: Symmetrical Variation, Three Knights Variation"]
[StudyName "Zwischenzug | Game of the Week"]
[ChapterName "Eric's Classical Tournament Games: Eric (953) vs Bruce Draney (1835) Nebraska HO"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/gL3s57BD/o2SR7Yo3"]

{ So going into this tournament I have been doing quite a bit of Sports Psychology training. Working on my mindset going into this pressure filled tournament. The main thing I kept telling myself is to look at it like I went to a casino, and as I walked in they gave me $2000 to gamble with. It's house money, no pressure if you lose it all, but you have the potential to win some back.
I have also been working on breathing exercises, anxiety is the killer of logical thinking so by slowing my heart rate and increasing oxygen to my blood stream, it helps me think more clearly.

Process goals for this tournament were:
In rounds 1 and 2 the time control is G75/+15, My goal was to be at 65:00 by move 10
20- 45:00
30-25:00
40- 10:0-15:00 minutes.

This gives me enough time to work in the endgame and not be in a time scramble. I need to do better at time management.

Achieving these process goals will help activate dopamine in my mind and help with mind clarity as well.

On to the game:
In this first game I played against Bruce Draney rated 1835 and a member of the Nebraska Hall of Fame Class. I went into this game trusting in my preperation and under the mentality that Bruce is going to have to prove that he can beat me. I am going to play calmly, under control, solid, and simple. Keep it simple.
Opening:
We played a Reversed Sicilian variation of the English Opening. One that I see often enough online and I feel like I know the plans well enough to strike when the iron is hot and when my opponent gives me an opportunity.
-Middlegame
The middlegame was intense, although I gave Bruce plenty of chances to hang himself, he just didn't pick up the rope and was able to defend nicely.
-Endgame:
Bruce had two passed pawns on the c and a files. I had to create counterplay and got into time trouble in the end and traded off the knights which allowed him to promote his pawn to a queen.

Honesty Check:
I trusted my preparation, I made Bruce prove that he could beat me, that mentality carried me through the game and I feel like I played just as well as he did, but the time scramble messed me up. I feel like my tactics and calculation were superb and that I gave everything that I had in this game. No complaints at all. My first round games are getting closer to becoming wins for me. I just need to tighten up the area of my game that is holding me back and then I will be converting some of these games. }
